Chrome is unshipping its implementation of the HTML Sanitizer API while a significant specification update is being worked on (see https://chromestatus.com/feature/5115076981293056).

This PR updates the BCD to account for this.

I've not listed the features as deprecated, as in this case the API is not being removed, rather it is being updated significantly.

items.content_html:
Summary

All versions of Internet Explorer only support the pre-CSS Fonts Module Level 3 syntax, meaning that it only recognises the small-caps and normal keywords.

This is a stark difference compared to the other browsers listed, and non-obvious unless you know to cross-reference with the font-variant shorthand compat data and what the functional differences are between font-variant and font-variant (but shorthand).

Although IE compat data is no longer actively maintained, flagging this difference (in an albeit high-level, not particularly nuanced way) could help avoid misunderstandings about IE's support for this property.

Test results and supporting details

  • IE 11 devtools only lists small-caps and normal keywords for autocompletion for font-variant.
  • No other font-variant values work in IE 11 or IE 10. (I could not easily test earlier versions).
items.title: Add note to IE support for `font-variant` CSS property

items.content_html:
Summary

The new script does the following:

  • Read a specific chromestatus page to get information about current, nightly, and beta versions of Chrome for Desktop and Chrome for Android
  • "Guess" (and check) the URL for the release notes of the last current Chrome for desktop / Chrome for android
  • update the local BCD files chrome.json and chrome_android.json

Once landed, the goal is to run it once and manually create a PR for the change. After this, the plan is to add an action to do that automatically and create a PR with the change to the browser fiels.

Notes:

  • script should be run in the directory containing "chrome.json" / "chrome_android.json".
  • I found a chromestatus bug that returns an invalid JSON file. This script works around the problem. This is well commented on in the bug. We will follow up with Google, but not blocking
  • There is no definitive way to find the URL of the release notes, so I guess it (in a function where I test if it works, checking if the page HTTP status is 200).
  • Assumed that:
    • "stable" in chromestatus is "release" in BCD
    • "beta" is "beta"
    • "dev" (and not "canary") is "nightly"
      These are constants in the code, so it is trivial to change this mapping
  • Errors and warning are logged on the console; this will be done while working on using it as a GitHub action.
  • Chromestatus doesn't have the whole history of release: if there is a gap, the script will log a warning.

Test results and supporting details

Manually tested.

Related issues

Part of the automation project.
items.title: Add script to update Chrome.json with new version
